        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="gkv100fig2"/>
      </fig>
    </sec>
    <sec id="SEC3-3">
      <title>Parameter selection</title>
      <p>In our Bayesian inference framework for modeling chromatin structures, the parameters, including experimental noise σ and the exponential component α for converting interaction frequencies to spatial distances, can be estimated in a rational way, as described in Algorithm 1. Here, we used the test on chromosome 1 of yeast as an example to demonstrate how our algorithm chooses the best estimates of these parameters. We plotted a distribution of the ensemble likelihood (which was calculated using Equation (<xref ref-type="disp-formula" rid="M15">15</xref>)) versus different choices of the parameters, as shown in Figure <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F3">3</xref>. The plotted histograms show how different choices of the parameters can affect the overall ensemble likelihood. For both α and <inline-formula><tex-math id="M49">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
